Headline: WSJA(5/14) Indian Magnate Nears Pact To Buy Whyte & Mackay
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By Deborah Ball in London and Eric Bellman in Mumbai   Indian entrepreneur and beer magnate Vijay Mallya is close to an agreement to purchase distiller Whyte & Mackay of Scotland for about GBP 600 million, or about $1 billion, according to people familiar with the matter.   People familiar with the negotiations between Mr. Mallya's UB Group and Whyte & Mackay said some details of the acquisition were still being worked out. Talks between the two companies became public last year. Mr. Mallya, chairman of UB Group, which includes India's biggest beer and whiskey makers as well as a two-year-old airline, is scheduled to hold a news conference in Glasgow on Wednesday. UB officials declined comment. Representatives of Whyte & Mackay couldn't be reached.   At GBP 600 million, the purchase would be one of the five largest international acquisitions ever by an Indian company, demonstrating the nation's growing economic power and importance in the global economy. After years when they focused on their home markets, many large Indian companies have made significant overseas acquisitions in the past few years.   Whyte & Mackay's brand of Scotch has lost its luster in the U.K., but the distiller is the biggest producer of private-label Scotch. With the acquisition Mr. Mallya could bring the Whyte & Mackay brand to India, where it would carry more cachet, and could use the private-label supplies to create new Scotch brands for the Indian market.   International whiskey brands could become another big source of income for UB Group, analysts said, as India is expected to lower its import tariffs on alcohol over the next two years. Tariffs on imported alcohol can run from 100% to 500% in India.   Mr. Mallya is perhaps India's most flamboyant entrepreneur. Earlier this month, his Kingfisher Airlines, one of the many new Indian airlines to have appeared in the past several years, brought a new double-decker Airbus 380 to India. He hosted demonstration flights out of New Delhi and Mumbai. Kingfisher is the only Indian airline to sign up so far for the new plane, ordering five, the first of which will be delivered in 2011.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  May 13, 2007 17:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Story: PARIS (Dow Jones)--Societe Generale SA (13080.FR) Chairman Daniel Bouton told representatives from labor union Confederation Generale du Travail that a tie-up with UniCredit SpA (UC.MI) would be "intelligent," according to French Sunday newspaper Le Journal du Dimanche.   During a meeting with union representatives, Bouton also said the French bank has identified eight possible tie-up partners in Europe, including Unicredit, the newspaper also reported.   Bouton added that, considering the Italian bank is larger that Societe Generale, Unicredit would more likely launch a takeover bid for SocGen than the other way round, according to union representatives quoted by the paper.   The paper didn't name which union representatives it had spoken to.   Societe Generale was not immediately available for comment.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.lejdd.fr     -By Paris Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 33-1-4017 1740     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  May 13, 2007 09:59 ET (13:59 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: India's Jet Airways To Raise $400 Mln Via Rights Issue
Story: MUMBAI (Dow Jones)--Jet Airways Ltd. (532617.BY), India's largest airline by market share, Sunday said it plans to raise $400 million via a rights issue to reduce its debt, meet working capital requirements and fund expansion plans.   Vic Dungca, member of Jet's board of directors, told reporters that the company is currently putting together proposals from investment bankers and will finalize details of the rights issue in a couple of weeks.   "Once we finalize the details, we can go to the board for approval, after which it would take about four months for the rights issue," Dungca said on the sidelines of a press conference where the company showcased its new aircraft for international operations.   He added that the founders of the Mumbai-based company may also consider a stake dilution at higher valuations to fund the expansion of its international operations.   "Today we're going in the direction of no dilution, but as the stock price improves we may want to sell shares to the public," he said.    Earlier in April, Jet had said it plans to raise up to $400 million in the next few months to fund the expansion of its international operations.   The company, which is launching its international route to London, also plans to fly from India to New York, Chicago, Toronto and Los Angeles in about eight to nine months, Jet Chairman Naresh Goyal said, adding that flights to Shanghai will also start soon.   The company is also planning to begin flights to the Middle East in 2008 after getting regulatory clearances from the federal government, Goyal said.   "In about five years, half our revenues would be from international operations. By that time, we should have revenues of $3 billion-$4 billion," Goyal said.   The company is also in talks with German carrier Lufthansa to start a cargo airline by the end of 2007, he said, without elaborating.   Speaking about its acquisition of rival Sahara Airlines Ltd., also popularly known as Air Sahara, Goyal said that Jet will spend $50 million to rebrand Sahara Airlines as JetLite and refurbish the fleet.   Jet Airways bought Sahara Airlines in April for INR14.50 billion.   Dungca added that Jet hopes to launch JetLite in about two months.   Separately, federal Civil Aviation Minister Praful Patel said the Indian government is planning to shortly bring out a new policy for the fast-growing domestic aviation industry.   "We are coming with a Vision 2020 (statement), which will spell out in a couple of months lots of issues that are not yet resolved," Patel said, without elaborating.   He added that he will also take up the issue of high turbine fuel prices with the federal oil ministry.     -By John Satish Kumar and Romit Guha; john.kumar@dowjones.com; +91-99001-81471     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  May 13, 2007 09:16 ET (13:16 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
